			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Incremental packrat parsing</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/PatrickDubroy.html">Patrick Dubroy</a>, <a href="../profile/AlessandroWarth.html">Alessandro Warth</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136022">10.1145/3136014.3136022</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4d.html"><span class="tagM">T4D: Interpretation</span></a><ul><li> The paper turns packrat parsing into an incremental parser, a runtime parsing technique for interactive settings.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Incrementality is pursued to improve performance when repeatedly parsing small edits.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagL">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> Incremental parsing is primarily motivated by editor/IDE tooling that needs fast feedback.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Packrat parsing is tied to PEG-style grammar formalisms, which serve as the underlying meta-language.
</li></ul></li></ul>
